 Community Survey 3-Year Estimates|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref> | [[Philadelphia]]<ref name=PhiladelphiaGreeks>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/12_3YR/S0201/330M100US428/popgroup~536|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212085136/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/12_3YR/S0201/330M100US428/popgroup~536|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 12, 2020|title=SELECTED POPULATION PROFILE IN THE UNITED STATES 2010-2012 American Community Survey 3-Year Estimates|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref> | [[Detroit]]<ref name=DetroitGreeks>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/12_3YR/S0201/330M100US220/popgroup~536|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212082420/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/12_3YR/S0201/330M100US220/popgroup~536|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 12, 2020|title=SELECTED POPULATION PROFILE IN THE UNITED STATES 2010-2012 American Community Survey 3-Year Estimates|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref> | [[Miami]]<ref name=MiamiGreeks>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/13_3YR/S0201/330M200US370/popgroup~536|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212085655/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/13_3YR/S0201/330M200US370/popgroup~536|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 12, 2020|title=SELECTED POPULATION PROFILE IN THE UNITED STATES 2011-2013 American Community Survey 3-Year Estimates|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref> | [[Tampa]]<ref name=TampaGreeks>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/12_3YR/S0201/310M100US45300/popgroup~536|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212082847/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/12_3YR/S0201/310M100US45300/popgroup~536|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 12, 2020|title=SELECTED POPULATION PROFILE IN THE UNITED STATES 2010-2012 American Community Survey 3-Year Estimates|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref>}}\n|languages  = {{hlist| [[American English]] | [[Greek language|Greek]] }}\n|religions  = Mostly [[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox]], with minorities practicing [[Greek Byzantine Catholic Church|Byzantine Catholicism]] and [[Judaism]] \n|related    = \n}}\n'''Greek Americans''' ({{lang-el|\u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03bf\u03b1\u03bc\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03af}}, ''Ellinoamerikanoi'') are [[Americans]] of full or partial [[Greeks|Greek]] ancestry. Over  1.4 million Americans are of Greek descent.<ref name=\"TAR2010\" /> 321,444 people older than five spoke [[Greek language|Greek]] at home in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apps.mla.org/cgi-shl/docstudio/docs.pl?map_data_results|title=Greek: Source: American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates, Public Use Microdata Sample, 2006\u20132010|publisher=[[Modern Language Association]]|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGreek Americans have the highest concentrations in the [[New York City metropolitan area|New York City]],<ref name=NYCGreeks/><ref name=\"dhs.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/yearbook-immigration-statistics-2012-legal-permanent-residents|title=Yearbook of Immigration Statistics: 2012 Supplemental Table 2|publisher=U.S. Department of Homeland Security|accessdate=April 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/files/statistics/publications/LPR09.shtm|title=Yearbook of Immigration Statistics: 2009 - Supplemental Table 2|accessdate=April 24, 2010}}</ref> [[Boston metropolitan area|Boston]],<ref name=BostonGreeks/> and [[Chicago metropolitan area|Chicago]]<ref name=ChicagoGreeks/> regions, but have settled in major [[metropolitan area]]s across the United States. In 2000, [[Tarpon Springs, Florida]] was home to the highest per capita representation of Greek Americans in the country (25%). The United States is home to the largest Greek community outside of [[Greece]], ahead of [[Australia]], [[Cyprus]], [[Albania]], [[Canada]], [[Germany]], and the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:Greek american Migrant - late 19th--20th century.jpg|thumb|180px|A young [[Greeks|Greek]] [[immigrant]] on [[Ellis Island]], [[New York City]], late 19th century]]\n\nThe first Greek known to have been to what is now the United States was Don Doroteo Teodoro, a sailor who landed in Boca Ciega Bay at the Jungle Prada site in present-day St. Petersburg, FL with the [[Narv\u00e1ez expedition]] in 1528. <ref> {{cite book| last= MacDougald |first= James | title= The P\u00e1nfilo de Narv\u00e1ez Expedition of 1528 | date= 2018 | publisher= Marsden House | location= St. Petersburg, FL | isbn= 978-1-4834-8671-0}} </ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.txstate.edu/swwc/cdv/book/25.html|title=Cabeza de Vaca's La Relacion|publisher=|accessdate=March 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.txstate.edu/swwc/cdv/book/29.html|title=Cabeza de Vaca's La Relacion|publisher=|accessdate=March 17, 2015}}</ref> He was instrumental in building the rafts that the expedition survivors built and sailed from present-day St. Mark's River in Florida until they were shipwrecked near Galveston Island, Texas. Teodoro had been captured by natives as they sailed along the Gulf coast shoreline toward the west, and was never seen again. <ref> {{cite book|last= Adorno |first= Rolena |author2=Pautz, Patrick |title= \u00c1lvar N\u00fa\u00f1ez Cabeza de Vaca: His Account, His Life, and the Expedition of Panfilo de Narv\u00e1ez |date= 1999-09-15 |publisher= [[University of Nebraska Press]] |location= Lincoln |isbn= 978-0-8032-1463-7 }}, 3 vols.</ref>\n\nIn 1592, Greek captain [[Juan de Fuca]] (Ioannis Fokas or Apostolos Valerianos) sailed up the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] coast under the Spanish flag, in search of the fabled [[Northwest Passage]] between the Pacific and the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]]. He reported discovering a body of water, a [[strait]] which today bears his name: the [[Strait of Juan de Fuca]], which today forms part of the [[Canada\u2013United States border]].\n\nAbout 500 Greeks from [[Smyrna]], [[Crete]], and [[Mani Peninsula|Mani]] settled in [[New Smyrna Beach, Florida]] in 1768. The colony was unsuccessful, and the settlers moved to [[St. Augustine, Florida|St. Augustine]] in 1776. The [[St. Photios Greek Orthodox National Shrine|St Photios Greek Chapel]] exists as a remnant of their presence, and is believed to be the oldest still standing Greek Orthodox religious structure in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|last=Leonard|first=M. C. Bob|url=http://floridahistory.org/british.htm|title=The Floridians: British Colonialism in Florida 1763-1783|publisher=floridahistory.org|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Leonidas C.|last=Polopolus|url=http://web.classics.ufl.edu/CGS/florida_hellenism.htm|title=A Brief History of Hellenism in Florida|publisher=University of Florida, Center for Greek Studies|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020224212339/http://web.classics.ufl.edu/CGS/florida_hellenism.htm|archivedate=February 24, 2002}}</ref>\n\n===19th century===\n[[File:Greek-American volunteers in the Balkan Wars.jpg|thumb|180px|Greek-American volunteers in the Balkan Wars]]\n\nThe first significant Greek community to develop was in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]] during the 1850s. By 1866, the community was numerous and prosperous enough to have a Greek [[Consul (representative)|consulate]] and the first official [[Greek Orthodox Church]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greekfestnola.com/churchhistory.html|title=History of the Holy Trinity Cathedral|publisher=greekfestnola.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520215428/http://www.greekfestnola.com/churchhistory.html|archivedate=May 20, 2007}}</ref> During that period, most Greek immigrants to the [[New World]] came from [[Anatolia|Asia Minor]] and those [[Aegean Islands]] still under [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule. By 1890, there were almost 15,000 Greeks living in the U.S.\n\nImmigration picked up again in the 1890s and early 20th century, due largely to economic opportunity in the U.S., displacement caused by the hardships of [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule, the [[Balkan Wars]], and [[World War I]]. Most of these immigrants had come from southern Greece, especially from the Peloponnesian provinces of Laconia and Arcadia.<ref name=\"Barkan1999\">{{cite book|last=Barkan|first=Elliott Robert|title=A Nation of Peoples: A Sourcebook on America's Multicultural Heritage|url=https://archive.org/details/nationofpeopless00bark|url-access=registration|year=1999|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-29961-2|pages=[https://archive.org/details/nationofpeopless00bark/page/252 252]\u2013253}}</ref> 450,000 Greeks arrived to the States between 1890 and 1917, most working in the cities of the [[northeastern United States]]; others labored on railroad construction and in mines of the [[western United States]]; another 70,000 arrived between 1918 and 1924. Each wave of immigration contributed to the growth of [[Hellenistic philosophy|Hellenism]] in the U.S.\n\nGreek immigration at this time was over 90% male, contrasted with most other European immigration to the U.S., such as [[Italians|Italian]] and [[Irish people|Irish]] immigration, which averaged 50% to 60% male. Many Greek immigrants expected to work and return to their [[homeland]] after earning capital and dowries for their families. However, the loss of their homeland due to the [[Greek Genocide]] and the 1923 [[population exchange between Greece and Turkey]], which displaced 1,500,000 Greeks from [[Anatolia]], [[Eastern Thrace]], and [[Pontus (region)|Pontus]] caused the initial economic immigrants to reside permanently in America. The Greeks were [[de jure]] denaturalized from their homelands and lost the right to return, and their families were made refugees. Additionally, the first widely implemented [[Immigration Act of 1924|U.S. immigration limits against non Western European immigrants]] were made in 1924, creating an impetus for immigrants to apply for citizenship, bring their families and permanently settle in the U.S. Fewer than 30,000 Greek immigrants arrived in the U.S. between 1925 and 1945, most of whom were \"[[Mail-order bride|picture brides]]\" for single Greek men and family members coming over to join relatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mpa.gr/specials/us_hellenes/micra_asia.html|script-title=el:\u039a\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03b5\u03b3\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03b9 \u0388\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7 \u039c. \u0391\u03c3\u03af\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u0397\u03a0\u0391|trans-title=Persecuted Greeks from Asia Minor in the USA|language=el|publisher=mpa.gr|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040807140929/http://www.mpa.gr/specials/us_hellenes/micra_asia.html|archivedate=August 7, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Steve|last=Frangos|url=http://www.pahh.com/frangos/brides.html|title=Picture Bride Era in Greek American History|publisher=The National Herald|via=Preservation of American Hellenic History|date=March 12, 2005|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:Sponge auction in Tarpon Springs (9190026157).jpg|thumb|220px|Sponge auction in [[Tarpon Springs, Florida]] in 1947. The community has the highest percentage of Greek Americans of any city in the US]]\n\nThe events of the early 1920s also provided the stimulus for the first permanent national Greek American religious and civic organizations. Greeks again began to arrive in large numbers after 1945, fleeing the economic devastation caused by [[World War II]] and the [[Greek Civil War]]. From 1945 until 1982, approximately 211,000 Greeks emigrated to the United States. These later immigrants were less influenced by the powerful assimilation pressures of the 1920s and 1930s and revitalized Greek American identity, especially in areas such as Greek-language media.\n\nGreek immigrants founded more than 600 [[diner]]s in the New York metropolitan area in the 1950s through the 1970s. Immigration to the United States from Greece peaked between the 1950s and 1970.<ref>{{cite news|first=Joseph|last=Berger|title=Diners in Changing Hands; Greek Ownership on the Wane|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/16/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/16Rdinersnj.html|work=[[New York Times]]|date=March 16, 2008|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Dena|last=Kleiman|title=Greek Diners, Where Anything Is Possible|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/27/garden/greek-diners-where-anything-is-possible.html?pagewanted=all|quote=... Greeks became a visible presence in the diner and coffee shop business in the late 1950s after several waves of immigration. They congregated largely on the East Coast, where the food service industry provided an easy economic foothold for many immigrants who were often unskilled and unable to speak English. As with immigrants from many nations, one relative would send word of opportunity back home, encouraging others to come to America|work=[[New York Times]]|date=February 27, 1991|accessdate=May 27, 2009}}</ref> After the 1981 admission of Greece to the [[European Union]], annual U.S. immigration numbers fell to less than 2,000. In recent years, Greek immigration to the United States has been minimal; in fact, net migration has been towards Greece. Over 72,000 U.S. citizens currently live in Greece (1999); most of them are Greek Americans.\n\nThe predominant religion among Greeks and Greek Americans is [[Greek Orthodox Church|Greek Orthodox Christianity]]. There are also a number of Americans who descend from [[Greece]]'s smaller [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardic]] and [[Romaniotes|Romaniote]] [[Jew]]ish communities.\n\n===21st century===\nIn the aftermath of the [[Greek financial crisis]], there has been a resurgence of [[Greek diaspora|Greek emigration]] to New York City since 2010, accelerating in 2015, and centered upon the traditional Greek enclave of [[Astoria, Queens]].<ref name=GreekResurgenceNewYork>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/06/world/greeks-in-new-york-talk-and-cheer-then-debate-future-after-referendum.html|title=Greeks in New York Talk and Cheer, Then Debate Future After Referendum|author=Annie Correal and Colleen Wright|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 5, 2015|accessdate=July 5, 2015}}</ref> According to ''[[The New York Times]]'', this new wave of Greek migration to New York is not being driven as much by opportunities in New York as it is by a lack of economic options in Greece itself.<ref name=GreekResurgenceNewYork/>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Bar chart\n| title       = Number of Greek Americans \n| label_type  = Year\n| data_type   = Number\n| bar_width   = 15\n| width_units = em\n| data_max    = 1500000\n| float       = right\n| label1   = 1980<ref>{{cite web|title=Rank of States for Selected Ancestry Groups with 100,00 or more persons: 1980|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/censusdata/files/pc80-s1-10/tab04.pdf|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=November 30, 2012}}</ref> \n| data1    = 959,856\n| label2   = 1990<ref>{{cite web|title=1990 Census of Population Detailed Ancestry Groups for States|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/cen1990/cp-s/cp-s-1-2.pdf|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=30 November 2012|date=September 18, 1992}}</ref> \n| data2    = 1,110,373\n| label3   = 2000<ref>{{cite web|title=Ancestry: 2000|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_00_SF3_QTP13&prodType=table|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212213043/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_00_SF3_QTP13&prodType=table|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 12, 2020|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=November 30, 2012}}</ref> \n| data3    = 1,153,307\n| label4   = 2010<ref>{{cite web|title=Total ancestry categories tallied for people with one or more ancestry categories reported 2010 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_10_1YR_B04003&prodType=table|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150118121537/http://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=ACS_10_1YR_B04003&prodType=table|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 18, 2015|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=November 30, 2012}}</ref> \n| data4    = 1,316,074\n}}\n\n[[File:Greek1346.gif|thumb|260px|[[Maps of American ancestries|Distribution]] of Greek Americans according to the [[United States Census, 2000|2000 census]]]]\n[[Image:Top of Rock Cropped.jpg|thumb|right|The [[New York City Metropolitan Area]], including [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], and [[Bergen County]], [[New Jersey]], is home to the largest Greek population in the United States.<ref name=NYCGreeks/><ref name=\"dhs.gov\"/>]]\n[[File:Archbishop Demetrios & POTUS GWBush, 2007March23.jpg|thumb|US President [[George W. Bush]] welcomes Archbishop Demetrios to the White House to celebrate Greek Independence Day and to recognize the contributions of Greek-Americans to American culture in March 2007]]\n\n===Population by state===\nPopulation by state according to the 2011-2015 [[American Community Survey]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2011-2015 American Community Survey Selected Population Tables |url=https://www.census.gov |accessdate=10 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\n#{{flag|New York}} \u2013 {{nts|148,637}}\n#{{flag|California}} \u2013 {{nts|133,680}}\n#{{flag|Illinois}} \u2013 {{nts|98,509}}\n#{{flag|Florida}} \u2013 {{nts|90,347}}\n#{{flag|Massachusetts}} \u2013 {{nts|83,701}}\n#{{flag|New Jersey}} \u2013 {{nts|63,940}}\n#{{flag|Pennsylvani