r, Kyle F. ''A Rabble in Arms: Massachusetts Towns and Militiamen during King Philip's War'' (New York: New York University Press, 2009) [https://archive.org/details/rabbleinarmsmass00zeln excerpt and text search]\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book |last=Delucia |first=Christine M. |year=2018 |title=Memory Lands: King Philip's War and the Place of Violence in the Northeast |url=https://yalebooks.yale.edu/book/9780300201178/memory-lands |location=New London, Conn. |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=9780300201178 |oclc=982566405}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* Peters, Paula, [http://www.capecodonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20020714/NEWS01/307149989&cid=sitesearch \"We Missed You\"], ''[[Cape Cod Times]]'', July 14, 2002\n<!-- * [http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~massasoit/causes.htm \"Edward Randolph on the Causes of the King Philip's War (1685)\"], ''[[rootsweb.com]]''. Dead link - commenting out in case an alternative URL is later found. -->\n* [https://archive.org/details/indianhistorybio00peir_0/page/141 <!-- quote=Killed march 26, 1676. --> King Philip's War] in Peirce, Ebenezer Weaver, [https://archive.org/details/indianhistorybio00peir_0 ''Indian history, biography and genealogy: pertaining to the good sachem Massasoit of the Wampanoag tribe, and his descendants''], Z.G. Mitchell, 1878\n* [https://archive.org/details/earlyrecordslan00masgoog/page/n328 <!-- quote=Killed march 26, 1676. --> Records of Lancaster, Massachusetts, p.324]\n\n{{Portal bar|England|Indigenous peoples of the Americas|North America|War}}<!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please do not add \"Portal:British Empire\" or \"Portal:United States\" as it would be historically inaccurate. Thank you. -->\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:King Philip's War| ]]\n[[Category:1670s conflicts]]\n[[Category:1670s in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:1675 in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:1676 in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:1677 in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:1678 in the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Colonial Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Colonial American and Indian wars]]\n[[Category:Colonial Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Colonial Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:History of Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:History of Springfield, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:Narragansett tribe]]\n[[Category:Wampanoag tribe]]\n[[Category:Native American history of Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Native American history of Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Native American history of Rhode Island]]\n", "name_user": "Regulov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlymouth Plantation Campaign", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King_Philip%27s_War"}
{"title_page": "Mendhar Tehsil", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{infobox settlement\n| name                            = Mendhar\n| native_name                     = \n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name                      = Dharamsal\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| nickname                        = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Jammu and Kashmir#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Jammu and Kashmir, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|33.60|N|74.11|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|Union Territory]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of Jammu and Kashmir|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Poonch district, India|Poonch]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_footnotes            = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| leader_party                    = [[JKNC]]\n| leader_title                    = [[Member of Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| leader_name                     = Shri Javed Ahmed Rana.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jklegislativeassembly.nic.in|title=members}}</ref>\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_total                = \n| population_as_of                = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_demonym              = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Urdu]] \n| demographics1_title2            = Other\n| demographics1_info2             = [[Gujari language|Gujari]], [[Pahari language|Pahari]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 185211\n| area_code                       = 911965\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = JK-12\n| footnotes                       = \n| type                            = Tehsil\n}}\n\n'''Mendhar''' is a [[tehsil]] (administrative district) in the [[Poonch district, India|Poonch district]] of the [[India]]n [[States and union territories of India|union territory]] of [[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]]. It is located in the foothills of [[Pir Panjal]] range within the [[Himalayas]]. The Mendhar Tehsil headquarters is in Mendhar town. It is located {{cvt|60|km}} south of the [[Poonch district, India|Poonch]] district headquarters and {{cvt|210|km}} from the state winter capital [[Jammu]].\n\n<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2014/20141006/main1.htm Heavy firing by Pak troops in Poonch], The Tribune, 5 October 2014.</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Mendhar-map-360 1 (1).jpg|thumb|Mendhar on Jammu and Kashmir map]]\nThe highest summer temperature is in between {{cvt|19|-|43|\u00b0C}} . \n\nThe average temperature in January is {{cvt|11|\u00b0C}}; February is {{cvt|13|\u00b0C}}; March is {{cvt|19|\u00b0C}}; April is {{cvt|24|\u00b0C}}; and May is {{cvt|30|\u00b0C}}.\n\n==Demography==\nThe total projected population of Mendhar Tehsil is 112,723, with 57,723 males and 55,000 females according to the [[2011 census of India]]. The population includes [[Pahari people|Pahari]]s, [[Gujjar]]s, [[Bakerwal]]s and [[Kashmiri people|Kashmiris]]. There are two blocks; Balakote and Mendhar. There are a total of 50 villages and 50 panchayats in Mendhar Tehsil.\n\n==Places of interest==\n\n===Krishna Ghati===\nKrishan Ghati is a hilly forest area, located {{cvt|30|km}} from Mendhar.<ref>[http://www.holidayiq.com/Krishna-Ghati-Poonch-Sightseeing-946-17848.html Krishna Ghati], Holiday IQ, Retrieved 2016-04-16.</ref> The site is known for its landscapes and natural environment.{{fact|date=February 2019}} The areas near it are dangerous due to continuous ceasefire violations.\n\n===Ziyarat Chhote Shah Sahib===\n[[Ziyarat]] Chhote Shah Sahib is located in the village Sakhi Maidan of Mendhar tehsil. This [[Ziyarat]] was built in memory of Saint Sakhi Peer Chhote Shah. A few hundred yards away lie the ruins of ancient architecture popularly believed to be of the Pandvas.<ref>[http://poonch.gov.in/TourismandReligiousplaces/ReligiousPlaces/muslim.html Muslim religious places], Poonch district government, Retrieved 2016-04-16.</ref>\n\n===Ram Kund===\nRam Kund is the oldest temple in [[Historical Poonch District|Poonch]] region. It is located in the village of Chajjla, {{cvt|6|km}} from Mendhar. This temple was built by [[Lalitaditya]] between 724 and 761.<ref>[http://kashmirparadise.blogspot.com/2009/03/ramkund-mandir-in-poonch.html Ramkund Mandir in Poonch], Kashir Paradise, Retrieved 2016-04-16.</ref> In  the temple's courtyard there are three sacred ponds, known as Ramkund, Lakshmankund and Sitakund. A water spring also emerges from Ramkund. Ramkund is {{cvt|8|-|19|km}} from Mendhar bus stand. Pilgrims visit during the month of March in [[Chaitra]] chawdish.<ref>[http://poonch.gov.in/BasicDetail/ReligiousPlaces/hindu.asp Hindu shrines] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421064256/http://poonch.gov.in/BasicDetail/ReligiousPlaces/hindu.asp |date=2014-04-21 }}, Poonch district government, Retrieved 2016-04-16.</ref>\n\n===Villages===\n[[Topa (Jammu and Kashmir)|Topa]] is a village located {{cvt|4|km}} from Mendhar. The Battle of Topa was fought here by the [[5 Gorkha Rifles]] during the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]].\n\nMankote is also one of the village of Mendhar.At mankote there is a defence Camp that provide facilities to the people of that village during any problem created due to shelling from Pakistan. \nCurrent sarpanch:Sayed Khan. \nThere is also a mosque.\nPopularly  known as Jummah Masjid Mankote.(TK) \n\n[[Balnoi]] is also a large village in Tehsil Mendhar. In 1947 mostly people of Balnoi migrated to Pakistan.\n\n\nChak Banola village is located at about 15 km from main City of Mendhar. It is considered as one of most fertile land for cultivation, encompassing a wide variety of floras. Chak Banola has  about 1500 population(2011 census).\nCurrent Sarpanch: Adv. Akbar Hussain khan\nNo of mosques: 6\n\nGazzeted officers: \n1.Prof. Rizwan ahmed,GDC Mendhar\n2.Shakeel Ahmed, lecturer GHSS Chattral\n3.Qadeer Ahmed, lecturer Diet poonch\n\nKalaban :\n Kalaban is a remote village of Mendher located 20&nbsp;km away from Mendher Tehsil \nSarpanch :Mohd Taj Bajjarh\nRoads Sakhi Madan to Chandak Kalai\nKalaban to poonch\nKalaban to Surankote\nBus Services : Daily Govt JKSRTC Bus Service From Kalaban to jammu\nNo of Mosque 7\nNo of Hospitals 1 (PHC)\n Languages : Gojjri 97%  Pahari 3%\nCasts: Mayana Bajjarh Sood Chouhan Boken Badhana chachi Mughal Qureshi \n\nFamous Personalities:\n Dr Masood Choudhary (IPS)\nOwais Rana (IAS)\nInzar Choudhary(KAS)\nJavaid Ahmed Rana (MLA)\nAshraf Choudhary (KAS)\nShahjahan Choudhary (KAS)\nDr Zahoor Rana (MBBS)\nSciencetist Dr Zabir Bajjarh\nExecutive Engineer Fareed Bajjarh\nAEE Parwaiz Rana\nAE Er Khursheed ul Islam\n\nEr Mahroof Ahmed Mayana\nEr Ishtiyaq Choudhary \nSSP Sarwar Chouhan (KPS)\nSSP Ab Ghani Kohli (KPS)\nHony Lt.Ihkhaq Mayana\nAdv Tariq Shareef Mayana\nSharaz Chouhan (KAS)\nNawaz Chouhan (KAS)\nHussain Ahmed Siddique (Senier govt Advocate)\nProf Dr Ateeq ul Rehman \nProf Dr Saleem Choudhary Mayana\nProf Dr Waseem ul Haq (p.hd physics IIT Delhi)\nProf Sarahad Hussain Shad (Zoology)\nZEO Mohd Rasheed Mayana\nAdvocate Mahroof Khan (pdp) and many many others\n\nFamous places in kalaban:\n 1)Ziarat Peer Ghulam shah badshah\n 2) Darbar peer Mehar Ali Shah\n 3) Pandwa\n 4) Fazlabad\n\nGrounds:\nMini  Cricket Stadium Kalaban\nSchools:\nGHSS Pathanteer\nGHSS Gali kalaban\nGHS Awan Kalaban\nGMS kalaban\nGMS Dharan kalaban\nRMMS kalaban\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Jammu and Kashmir-related articles]]\n* [[Surankote]]\n* [[Pir Panjal Range]]\n* [[Topa, Jammu and Kashmir]]\n\n{{JammuKashmir-geo-stub}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170915154945/http://jammukashmir.nic.in/ The Official Website of Jammu and Kashmir Government, India]\n* [http://poonch.gov.in/ Official Website of District Poonch, India]\n* [http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/jammuandkashmir/tehsil/poonch.html Poonch Tehsil map], mapsofindia.com.\n\n<!--start of Navigation boxes-->{{Clear}}\n{{Jammu and Kashmir}}\n{{Municipalities of Jammu and Kashmir}}\n<!--end of Navigation boxes-->\n\n[[Category:Poonch district, India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{infobox settlement\n| name                            = Mendhar\n| native_name                     = \n| native_name_lang                = \n| other_name                      = Dharamsal\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| nickname                        = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Jammu and Kashmir#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             =